<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n22086d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n22" href="#n22086d">N22 (VI.B.17)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n22all.htm#n22086d"> 86(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ Absolute Possib. ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">At a later stage of his philosophy, however, the Cusan gave a second deduction of the Trinity. God is both Absolute Possibility, Absolute Power or Potency (the Creative Word, the Son), and the union of both in Absolute Reality; yet these are merely different aspects or points of view of the Eternal Being. <small> J. Lewis McIntyre, <a name="BRUNO" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BRUNO"><cite title="source">Giordano Bruno</cite></a> (1903) 145</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
